Juneteenth is so much more than just a celebration (though it certainly is that). It’s about history, truth and liberation. I believe that mental health care is a part of that liberation–not a luxury, not an afterthought, but a critical part of true liberation. 

I want to share a few resources in Chicago that are doing culturally grounded work for Black folks–give them a follow & share: 

@Chicagoblacktherapists 
@sistaafya 
@blackgirlsbreakbread

The Bali most people see is the beach clubs, the scooters, the crowds in Canggu.

This is the other one.

Drive twenty minutes inland and the island changes completely. The noise drops away. The rice fields open up. And tucked into the river gorges, the volcano valleys and the jungle, there are stays that feel like they belong to a different Bali entirely.

A retreat built around its own waterfall, from bamboo and earth pulled out of the land it sits on. A bamboo house three storeys tall on the edge of the Ayung gorge, where you can hear the river from every room. Six rooms in the Sidemen Valley with Mount Agung standing straight ahead. A cluster of bamboo houses so far off the trail they hand you a scooter, because there is nothing within walking distance.

No televisions. Slow wifi, on purpose. Villages for neighbours.

These are the places that reset something. The ones you do not want to tell people about, then cannot stop talking about.

Seven of them. All hidden in the green.

Save this for the Bali trip that looks nothing like everyone else’s. Then tell us where you would start.

The crowds stay on the coast. The good part is inland.

